<Base
  title="Thesis"
  description="Why Falsafa uses markdown and MCP tools instead of an embedding index. The structural argument for the librarian-not-LLM design, with the eval data behind it."
  ogImage="/og/thesis.png"
>
  <article class="thesis-page">
    <header class="thesis-header">
      <p class="thesis-kicker">Thesis</p>
      <h1>Markdown and tools, not vector DBs.</h1>
      <p class="thesis-lede">
        For a curated archive of natural-language texts, an LLM
        navigating markdown through tools beats embedding-based
        retrieval. The corpus is small enough to index with traditional
        IR. The structure is too valuable to flatten into similarity.
        The citation has to resolve to a paragraph, not a chunk.
      </p>
      <p class="thesis-lede-meta">
        Eight tools. One Pagefind index, ~1MB. Stable paragraph IDs.
        Source at <a href="https://github.com/adoistic/falsafa/tree/main/apps/mcp/src">apps/mcp/src/</a>.
        Figures behind every claim at <a href="/numbers/">/numbers</a>.
        Live cases at <a href="/eval/">/eval</a>.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="thesis-section" id="setup">
      <h2><a href="#setup">1. The default RAG pipeline</a></h2>
      <p>
        The reflex when an AI builder hears "build a chatbot over this
        archive" is well-rehearsed: split the documents into chunks of
        roughly 512 tokens, embed each chunk with an off-the-shelf
        model, write the vectors into a vector database, retrieve the
        top-<em>k</em> chunks per query by cosine similarity, paste
        them into the LLM's context window with a "given the following
        excerpts" preamble, and call it RAG.
      </p>
      <p>
        That pipeline assumes four things at once. The corpus is too
        large to fit in any context window. The corpus has no
        usable structure (or its structure is hidden inside PDFs and
        HTML scrapes). The user query is the only navigation signal
        that matters. Cosine similarity on a contrastive
        general-purpose embedding model approximates relevance well
        enough.
      </p>
      <p>
        For a public dump of unstructured documents, those assumptions
        are roughly correct and the pipeline is roughly the right
        answer. For a curated archive of literary texts, every one of
        them is wrong.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="thesis-section" id="why-not">
      <h2><a href="#why-not">2. Why that's the wrong question for this archive</a></h2>

      <h3>Corpus size</h3>
      <p>
        Falsafa's corpus is 38 works. <a href="/numbers/">/numbers</a>
        gives the exact figures: 836 logical chapters, 2,089 variant
        entries (translation, transliteration, original), 76,303
        paragraphs, roughly 3M words summed across every variant.
        The Pagefind index Falsafa ships for full-text site search
        is around 1MB compressed. The whole metadata layer (per-work
        <code>index.md</code>, per-chapter <code>meta.json</code>,
        per-paragraph <code>*.paragraphs.json</code> sidecar) is a
        few megabytes. None of this needs an approximate-nearest-
        neighbour index. It fits in a directory.
      </p>
      <p>
        Vector retrieval was invented to solve a real problem: when
        the corpus is a hundred million documents and the question is
        "find me a few that are semantically near this one," you
        cannot scan. You quantize, you index, you take the cosine
        hit. For a corpus that fits in a build artifact, that
        machinery solves a problem you don't have, and pays the
        well-known costs (chunk-boundary noise, lossy embedding,
        index drift on re-ingest) anyway.
      </p>

      <h3>Curation flattens into similarity</h3>
      <p>
        Curation is the thing that took years. Each work in Falsafa
        carries an attested author, an era, a source language and
        script, a translator, a published year, a layout (prose or
        verse), and an ordered chapter sequence. Each chapter carries
        its variants (Old English original, Latin-script
        transliteration, English translation), each with its own
        paragraph sequence. None of that is in the body text. All of
        it is in the metadata.
      </p>
      <p>
        An embedding index sees the body text. It cannot answer "what
        works are by Cynewulf" without first finding chunks that
        happen to mention Cynewulf, which is not the same question.
        It cannot answer "list the Sanskrit smṛti texts" without a
        scan that the metadata answers in one filter. It cannot tell
        an Iqbal ghazal from its Urdu transliteration because the
        embedding space treats them as separate documents that
        coincidentally share concepts.
      </p>
      <p>
        Tools preserve the structure. <code>{`list_works({ author: "cynewulf" })`}</code>
        returns the three Old English Christian
        poems and nothing else. <code>list_chapters(work_slug)</code>
        returns the ordered chapter sequence. <code>get_metadata
        (work_slug)</code> returns the full provenance. No approximation,
        no chunk-boundary noise, no cosine threshold to tune.
      </p>

      <h3>Citation has to resolve to a paragraph</h3>
      <p>
        Vector RAG cites chunks. A chunk is a 512-token window inside
        a document, identified by a chunk index, a vector ID, or a
        score. A reader cannot follow that citation. They cannot open
        the chapter, scroll to the line, see what came before.
      </p>
      <p>
        Falsafa cites paragraphs by stable hash. Every paragraph in
        every variant carries a six-character FNV-1a hash of its
        content, prefixed <code>p-</code>. The reading site at
        <a href="/works/">/works/...#p-xxxxxx</a> resolves the hash to
        a highlighted line. The MCP's <code>read_chapter</code> tool
        annotates its output with <code>[p-xxxxxx]</code> markers so
        the host LLM can cite directly. The preprint records what
        happened before that fix landed: the model either invented
        identifiers that did not resolve, or it copied the inline
        verse markers (<code>Mn_1.52</code>) which are real but
        unaddressable. After the fix, every cited paragraph in the
        small-N run resolves.
      </p>
      <p class="thesis-aside">
        See <code>annotateBodyWithParagraphIds</code> in
        <a href="https://github.com/adoistic/falsafa/blob/main/apps/mcp/src/tools.ts">apps/mcp/src/tools.ts</a>
        for the actual injection. It's twenty lines.
      </p>

      <h3>Attribution: who runs the inference?</h3>
      <p>
        A vector-RAG system needs an embedding model at ingest time
        and (usually) an answer-synthesizing LLM at query time. Both
        cost money or run on someone's GPU. Both are model-specific:
        rebuild the index when the embedding model deprecates, retest
        the prompt when the synthesis model changes.
      </p>
      <p>
        Falsafa's MCP runs no LLM. The eight tools return text and
        structure. The host LLM, whichever the user installed in
        Claude Desktop or Cursor or Codex, does the reasoning.
        Falsafa does not pay inference. Falsafa does not get to
        choose the model. The user's preferred frontier LLM is the
        librarian's brain, and any improvement to that brain (Sonnet
        4.6 → 4.7, GPT-5 → 6) lifts every Falsafa session for free.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="thesis-section" id="instead">
      <h2><a href="#instead">3. What we did instead</a></h2>

      <p>
        The MCP server exposes eight tools. Each returns text plus
        structure; none calls an LLM internally.
      </p>

      <table class="thesis-tools">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Tool</th>
            <th>What it returns</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>list_works</td>
            <td>
              The catalogue, optionally filtered by era, author, language,
              genre, difficulty. Direct over the manifest.
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>list_chapters</td>
            <td>Ordered chapter sequence for a work, with available variants.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>get_metadata</td>
            <td>
              Full provenance for a work: author bio, era, layouts,
              variant types, the first eight chapter titles.
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>read_chapter</td>
            <td>
              The chapter body as markdown, annotated with stable
              <code>[p-xxxxxx]</code> identifiers at every paragraph.
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>get_passage</td>
            <td>
              Specific paragraphs by ID or range. The citation primitive.
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>search_corpus</td>
            <td>
              Pagefind-backed full-text search with an IDF-ranked
              auto-fallback for long queries that miss as a literal
              substring. AND-of-words by default; the fallback retries
              on the most distinctive 3 tokens.
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>find_related</td>
            <td>
              TF-IDF cosine-ranked cross-links built at ingest time, with
              a structural fallback (same author, same era, same genre).
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>compare_works</td>
            <td>
              Topic-restricted chapter pointers from each of two works.
              The host LLM does the comparison, not the server.
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>
        The shape of a typical session has nothing in common with the
        vector-RAG flow:
      </p>

      <div class="thesis-compare">
        <div class="thesis-compare-panel">
          <p class="thesis-compare-label">Vector RAG</p>
          <ol>
            <li>User query embedded</li>
            <li>Top-<em>k</em> chunks retrieved by cosine</li>
            <li>Chunks pasted into context</li>
            <li>LLM synthesizes from chunks</li>
            <li>Citation: chunk index or vector ID</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
        <div class="thesis-compare-panel is-ours">
          <p class="thesis-compare-label">Falsafa MCP</p>
          <ol>
            <li>LLM reads the question</li>
            <li>
              Calls <code>list_works</code> or <code>search_corpus</code>
              based on shape
            </li>
            <li>
              Reads candidate chapters with <code>read_chapter</code>
            </li>
            <li>Pulls exact paragraphs with <code>get_passage</code></li>
            <li>Citation: <code>work_slug</code> + <code>p-xxxxxx</code></li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Search is Pagefind, not embeddings. Pagefind is the static-site
        full-text index that ships ~1MB of compressed posting lists for
        the entire English layer. The MCP wraps it with two pieces of
        logic worth naming. First, the default scope is the English
        layer (translations plus native-English variants), with
        <code>scope: "all"</code> for transliteration and original-script
        searches. Second, when a literal-substring query of more than
        five words returns zero hits, the server falls back to scanning
        for the three most-distinctive tokens, ranked by inverse
        document frequency over the corpus's English layer.
        That auto-fallback catches the failure mode where an LLM
        searches for a long verbatim quote and misses by one comma. The
        IDF index builds in under 500ms at first query and stays
        memoised.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="thesis-section" id="works">
      <h2><a href="#works">4. Does it work?</a></h2>

      <p>
        The protocol and the early data live in the
        <a href="https://github.com/adoistic/falsafa/blob/main/docs/preprint/eval-paper-draft-2026-04-28.md">
          preprint draft (v0.1)</a>. Twelve adversarial questions, drawn
        stratified from the calibrated 1,000-case pool, each answered
        by an independent fresh Claude Sonnet 4.6 sub-agent session
        with only the Falsafa MCP attached. No codebase access, no
        ground-truth access, no shared memory between agents.
      </p>

      <dl class="thesis-stats">
        <div class="thesis-stat">
          <dt>11/12</dt>
          <dd>mechanical pass rate (92%)</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="thesis-stat">
          <dt>98/98</dt>
          <dd>citations resolving to real paragraph IDs</dd>
        </div>
        <div class="thesis-stat">
          <dt>0/98</dt>
          <dd>verse-marker citations (the pre-fix failure mode)</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>

      <p>
        The single mechanical fail (q-0401) is a known scorer
        artifact: the agent identified ten works substantively
        engaging the soul's-journey-after-death topic across four
        traditions; the expected-works list narrowed to five. The
        agent's answer was more complete than the rubric. The
        substantive judge layer corrects this kind of case, and is
        what the codex-CLI full-1000 run will reveal at scale.
      </p>
      <p>
        Browse the cases at <a href="/eval/">/eval</a>. Every cited
        paragraph deep-links to the highlighted line in the reader.
        The audit is the artifact.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="thesis-section" id="not-claiming">
      <h2><a href="#not-claiming">5. What we are not claiming</a></h2>
      <p>
        Twelve questions is a proof of protocol. It is not a
        confidence-bounded estimate of corpus coverage, and it does
        not yet support a head-to-head claim against vector RAG.
      </p>
      <p>
        The intellectually honest comparison is a hybrid baseline. We
        are building one at <code>apps/baseline/</code>: the same
        1,000-question pool, the same blind-sub-agent dispatch, but
        the agent is given a vector-retrieval tool over the same
        corpus instead of the Falsafa eight. When that lands, the
        eval explorer at <a href="/eval/">/eval</a> will show both
        rows side by side, per case, and any reader can verify the
        comparison. Until then, the structural argument on this page
        is an argument, not a measurement. We test the Falsafa side
        of it now, at the URLs above. The other half is forthcoming.
      </p>
      <p>
        Other limitations the preprint records explicitly: the
        small-N run uses a single model family (Sonnet 4.6); the
        Sonnet judge layer has not yet rescored the batch; Pagefind
        indexes the English layer by default, so cross-script lookups
        for non-English transliterated terms (<em>alast</em>,
        <em>paimaan-e-awwaleen</em>) currently rely on an explicit
        <code>scope: "all"</code> or filesystem fallback. A
        dedicated transliteration-layer index is a natural next step.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="thesis-section" id="karpathy">
      <h2><a href="#karpathy">6. The Karpathy nod</a></h2>
      <p>
        The framing of "tools return text and structure, the LLM does
        the reasoning" is not original to us. Andrej Karpathy
        proposed something close in his
        <a href="https://gist.github.com/karpathy/442a6bf555914893e9891c11519de94f">
          gist on LLM-maintained markdown wikis
        </a>: humans curate sources, the LLM does the bookkeeping
        that makes a knowledge base actually usable, and the wiki is
        a persistent compounding artifact rather than a chunk index
        rebuilt on every query.
      </p>
      <p>
        Falsafa runs the same shape on a different axis. The wiki is
        the corpus itself: every work, chapter, and paragraph is
        markdown with stable identifiers. The schema is the manifest
        and the per-chapter <code>meta.json</code>. The host LLM is
        the librarian, not a second LLM in our loop. The bookkeeping
        is the eight tools.
      </p>
      <p class="thesis-pullquote">
        For a curated archive, the wiki is not a place you put
        knowledge for the LLM to retrieve. It is the place where the
        LLM does its work.
      </p>
    </section>

